[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You are hearing it here first. We now have the power of iterative chatbased image editing like we have with Gemini and GPT. Now with the power and quality of the Flux Pro model. Welcome back to the channel where we discuss the'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creative uses of AI. And I am super excited to be among the first to show you this new Flux model that allows you to create images from scratch with it or iterate changes in existing images just with chatbased commands while leaving'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything you don\'t want changed completely intact. And the secret is in good prompting. Starting today, this new Flux Context Pro model is available over at Open Art. And you can use it in a couple of ways. You can certainly use it'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just like you would any other model by clicking on create image and choosing the Flux Context model from your list of models and just give it a prompt. Closeup of an old man playing the ukulele on a park bench in New York'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'City. For now, I\'m going to skip the Omni reference. I\'ll come back to that and then we\'ll choose an output size. I will go with cinema and click on create and get a couple of outputs. So now we\'ve got our flux generated images of'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this old man playing ukulele and it is great. Everything\'s coherent, right number of fingers, everything\'s nice quality. It\'s good. So if we just want to make one change to this and not do a whole series of changes, we can do that'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right here in this normal create interface by using the omni reference feature. Now, this allows you to drag in any image and start doing iterative chatbased editing to it using this prompt area. In this case, instead of bringing in an image from the outside,'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to refer to our history just by clicking on history here, choosing this guy here, and clicking on confirm. Once this image is in this omniresence area, now anything I type on here will act like a prompt to change it. Now, the'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'key with getting the results that you want with this, which is basically leaving the original image or anything you don\'t want changed completely alone, maintaining facial integrity and all of that, is a very specific prompt. You don\'t want to do generalized prompts'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because that gives it way too much flexibility to make some changes. That doesn\'t mean that simple prompts never work. So, if you really want to try one, we can do it. And we\'ll see how much it affects the overall image. So, let\'s just change this guy\'s cap to, let\'s say, a Chicago Cubs cap. And we\'ll use a'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very simple prompt. We\'ll just say change the cap to a Chicago Cubs cap. I won\'t mess with auto enhance or anything like that. And we\'ll click on create. If you\'ve used the flux models on Open Art'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before, you know that they\'re extremely fast. And this is no different. We get these in just a few seconds. And now you can see that we have the man in the same position and he is wearing the cap. And actually did a pretty good job. If we blow these up and go from image to'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image, it absolutely didn\'t change a thing. And that was with a simple prompt. But if we ever get into a situation during this demonstration where things are changing a little bit, we can be more specific with the prompt. But if you\'ve used any of these other'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chatbased image solutions before, you know that generally you get some kind of change. And every time you iterate, the face changes a little bit more or you lose some details. But you can see this acts like an inpainting. There\'s nothing that changes. Not one pixel other than'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the cap. And that is pretty amazing. Let\'s change the ukulele into a mandolin. But we want to use one of these images with the Chicago Cubs cap. At this time, if I was to try to change this and go to the history, it doesn\'t'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'show what we just did. And to be able to access that, I would just need to refresh this page. So then when I click on Omni Reference and click here, I can click on history. And now my changes with the Chicago Cubs cap are there. So'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
